217. Contains Duplicate
Problem

Given an integer array nums, return true if any value appears at least twice, otherwise return false.

Example
Input: nums = [1,2,3,1]
Output: true
Input: nums = [1,2,3,4]
Output: false
Approach 1: Brute Force
Intuition

Compare every element with every other element.

If any duplicate is found, return true.

Java
class Solution {
    public boolean containsDuplicate(int[] nums) {

        for (int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {

            for (int j = i + 1; j < nums.length; j++) {

                if (nums[i] == nums[j]) {
                    return true;
                }
            }
        }

        return false;
    }
}
Dry Run
nums = [1,2,3,1]
i	j	Compare	Duplicate?
0	1	1==2	No
0	2	1==3	No
0	3	1==1	✅ Yes

Return:

true
Complexity
Time: O(n²)
Space: O(1)
Approach 2: Sorting
Intuition

After sorting, duplicate elements become adjacent.

Simply compare neighboring elements.

Java
class Solution {
    public boolean containsDuplicate(int[] nums) {

        Arrays.sort(nums);

        for (int i = 1; i < nums.length; i++) {

            if (nums[i] == nums[i - 1]) {
                return true;
            }
        }

        return false;
    }
}
Dry Run

Input:

nums = [1,2,3,1]

After Sorting:

[1,1,2,3]

Compare:

1 == 1 ✓

Return:

true
Complexity
Time: O(n log n)
Space: O(1) (ignoring sorting implementation)
Approach 3: HashSet (Optimal)
Intuition

A HashSet stores only unique elements.

If an element already exists in the set, it is a duplicate.
Otherwise, add it to the set.

Java
class Solution {
    public boolean containsDuplicate(int[] nums) {

        HashSet<Integer> set = new HashSet<>();

        for (int num : nums) {

            if (set.contains(num)) {
                return true;
            }

            set.add(num);
        }

        return false;
    }
}
Alternative (Shortest Code)
class Solution {
    public boolean containsDuplicate(int[] nums) {

        HashSet<Integer> set = new HashSet<>();

        for (int num : nums) {
            if (!set.add(num)) {
                return true;
            }
        }

        return false;
    }
}

Why?

set.add(x)

returns

true → inserted successfully
false → already exists (duplicate)
Dry Run

Input:

nums = [1,2,3,1]
Number	HashSet	Duplicate?
1	{1}	No
2	{1,2}	No
3	{1,2,3}	No
1	Already Exists	✅ Yes

Return:

true
Complexity
Time: O(n)
Space: O(n)
Interview Summary
Approach	Time	Space
Brute Force	O(n²)	O(1)
Sorting	O(n log n)	O(1)*
HashSet (Optimal)	O(n)	O(n)

* Ignoring the sorting algorithm's internal space.

Key Trick

Use a HashSet to keep track of elements seen so far.

If element already exists
        ↓
Duplicate Found
        ↓
Return true
Pattern
Array
   ↓
Traverse Elements
   ↓
Check HashSet
   ↓
Already Present?
   ↓
Yes → Return true
No  → Add to Set
